<br>
That being said, I don't know what determines the range at which you can be from a targetted mob and get their name when you Hail them.  I don't know if it's aggro range based (seems to be much larger than that) or if it's simply some fixed range from your position. <p>Dalynia Aziz<br>
Arch Mage of Amici<br>
Innoruuk Server<br>
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=28865"><i>profile</i></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uetriganuspudicum.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Etriganus Pudicum</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Scowling Poster</span><br> <font color=#778899>(3/26/02 8:27:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/finnoruukserverfrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1456.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://mywebpages.comcast.net/PrinceEtrigan/ethed.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: HoT Door and other mysteries of life explained.</span><hr size=1> Nice theory Tol, too bad it's just that...theory.  Ask any engineer and they'll tell you what looks all nice and neat on paper generally isn't so neat in the field.  <br>
<br>
Knowledge of game mechanics aside, practical experience from countless hours of hunting in HoT have shown that if you fight a mob in front of the door and it's closed there's no aggro.  I've even been the last man standing directly in front of the door and getting hit by aoe which didn't aggro the drakes.  <br>
<br>
As for scientific method:<br>
<br>
Experiment after experiment, observation after observation the same thing is observed...fight in front of the door and open it, Zemm and pals assist the mob.  This is called confirmation of the phenomenon or PROOF that a condition exsists (ie it happens the same way each time).  Feel free to test it yourself...pull a wurm, drake, rancar, whatever right in front of the door and fight it then have someone open the door (I'll volunteer) and see what happens.  Then do the same thing while the door is shut, march the mob right up to the door, as long as it doesn't pop it's head through the door (thereby opening it in my theory of why this causes aggro) Zemm and friends couldn't care less.<br>
<br>
In a program as buggy and unstable as Everquest you can count on one thing, the unexpected.  It seems that by it's very nature Everquest behaves much like the real world in that there are exceptions to every rule...whether it's intended or not in this instance only the programmers at VI know for sure.<br>
<br>
So please, keep that door shut unless you want to be considered inconsiderate at best and a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> potatoe</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> at worst.<br>
